1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,200
 I can actually smell the pine from here, it's kind of cool.

2
00:00:03,200 --> 00:00:07,000
 I feel like I'm home for Christmas.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,680
 Well, when I was a young child,

4
00:00:10,680 --> 00:00:14,520
 I visited New York City with my family.

5
00:00:14,520 --> 00:00:18,240
 And on this trip to New York City, my mom,

6
00:00:18,240 --> 00:00:21,120
 she's the travel expert of our family.

7
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:24,760
 She does an amazing job. She reads like the travel guides,

8
00:00:24,760 --> 00:00:27,480
 gets prepared, it was a time before the internet.

9
00:00:27,480 --> 00:00:31,000
 So reading the travel guides and coming up with this incredible plan.

10
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,760
 So every day we had an amazing program as a family.

11
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:37,240
 Now one day there was lunch,

12
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:40,160
 and we're already a little bit hungry,

13
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:42,600
 and my mom says, "Hey, this guide there,

14
00:00:42,600 --> 00:00:46,800
 that recommends this place, let's go there."

15
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:48,760
 And so she insisted that we go there,

16
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:52,240
 even though there was all these amazing restaurants around us.

17
00:00:52,240 --> 00:00:55,240
 So we start walking, and we walk,

18
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:57,720
 and we walk past one nice-looking restaurant

19
00:00:57,720 --> 00:01:00,480
 where the food looks good after the other,

20
00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:02,720
 and I'm getting more hungry, and I remember as a kid,

21
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:04,800
 I'm like, "Why are we not stopping just eating here?

22
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:08,200
 This looks good. This looks great. I want to eat here."

23
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:10,000
 But we kept walking because she was determined.

24
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,280
 "We're going to follow what this guide says,

25
00:01:12,280 --> 00:01:13,680
 you know, we're going to eat there.

26
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:16,640
 It's highly recommended.

27
00:01:16,640 --> 00:01:19,920
 Yeah, so we need to go and eat what is highly recommended."

28
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:22,600
 So we finally get there,

29
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:27,000
 and the place does look very unimpressive.

30
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,360
 It's like, wow, maybe it's a hole in the wall place.

31
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:30,760
 That's amazing, right?

32
00:01:30,760 --> 00:01:33,240
 So at this point in time, we're just going to get food,

33
00:01:33,240 --> 00:01:36,120
 we order, receive our meals,

34
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:43,480
 and the food is absolutely incredible.

35
00:01:43,480 --> 00:01:46,840
 No, it was disastrous.

36
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:49,560
 It was the worst meal of the whole trip.

37
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:52,080
 It was horrible.

38
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:54,320
 Yeah, it was such a letdown, such a disappointment.

39
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:57,360
 Highly recommended, right?

40
00:01:57,360 --> 00:02:00,200
 And we were actually joking with my mom

41
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:01,920
 because she was so insistent,

42
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:03,760
 and we walked past all these other places.

43
00:02:03,760 --> 00:02:07,200
 We were kind of teasing her about what a bust,

44
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:09,720
 what a disappointment.

45
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:14,440
 Now, why am I telling you a story about a guide book,

46
00:02:14,440 --> 00:02:16,400
 you know, that leads us to a restaurant

47
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:22,360
 that turns out in an unfortunate eating event?

48
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:24,320
 And there's a reason for this,

49
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:30,880
 because who guides us in our lives matters.

50
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:32,560
 Who guides us in our lives matters.

51
00:02:32,560 --> 00:02:34,840
 Now, for a meal, that was no big deal, right?

52
00:02:34,840 --> 00:02:36,160
 You can have a bad meal,

53
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:40,200
 unless it can be very bad, right?

54
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:41,440
 But you just move on.

55
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:43,600
 It's okay. We left. We were fine.

56
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:45,840
 But what about the bigger things in life?

57
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:48,720
 What about the bigger things?

58
00:02:48,720 --> 00:02:51,280
 So, what I want to explore with you today is a question.

59
00:02:51,280 --> 00:02:56,480
 Who or what guides your life?

60
00:02:56,480 --> 00:02:58,760
 Like, who actually gives you direction right now?

61
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:02,280
 Is it a social media influencer?

62
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:05,040
 Is it your algorithm

63
00:03:05,040 --> 00:03:06,920
 that shapes and guides what you do,

64
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:09,000
 what you think is good, what you think you should do,

65
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,200
 how you think your life should be?

66
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:16,120
 Is it culture that keeps shifting,

67
00:03:16,120 --> 00:03:17,280
 where you just orient yourself,

68
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:19,480
 whatever everybody else is doing,

69
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:21,520
 that's what we're going to do?

70
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:26,120
 Or do you determine, are you the master of your own fate?

71
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:30,360
 Are you the one in charge of everything?

72
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:34,760
 Who or what guides your life?

73
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:37,640
 And how is that going, by the way?

74
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:40,800
 How is that working out for you?

75
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:44,400
 So, we're in our sermon series,

76
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:48,400
 our Advent Christmas sermon series, "I Am."

77
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:52,600
 And I want to set a little bit the background for this series.

78
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:54,920
 In the Gospel of John,

79
00:03:54,920 --> 00:03:57,440
 instead of having a birth narrative,

80
00:03:57,440 --> 00:04:01,040
 like the Gospel of Luke and the Gospel of Matthew,

81
00:04:01,040 --> 00:04:06,080
 John gives us a theological account of Jesus' coming,

82
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:10,400
 the Word made flesh, God incarnate.

83
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:15,480
 And I want to read to you from John 1, verse 14, it says this,

84
00:04:15,480 --> 00:04:19,920
 "The Word became flesh and made His dwelling among us.

85
00:04:19,920 --> 00:04:21,800
 We have seen His glory,

86
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:24,680
 the glory of the one and only Son

87
00:04:24,680 --> 00:04:31,840
 who came from the Father full of grace and truth."

88
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:34,480
 Now, each week in the series,

89
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:37,280
 we're unpacking what is the significance

90
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:39,880
 of the Word being made flesh.

91
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:42,880
 What's the significance of Jesus coming to us?

92
00:04:42,880 --> 00:04:45,880
 What is the significance of the incarnation?

93
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:50,080
 And so we want to explore that this Christmas season.

94
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:53,480
 And we're going to do it through the famous "I Am" statements

95
00:04:53,480 --> 00:04:55,720
 in the Gospel of John.

96
00:04:55,720 --> 00:04:58,160
 Last week, we had, "I am the light of the world."

97
00:04:58,160 --> 00:05:00,600
 These are declarations from Jesus.

98
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:02,560
 He's declaring who He is.

99
00:05:02,560 --> 00:05:04,680
 He's declaring why He came.

100
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:07,720
 He's declaring why we celebrate Christmas.

101
00:05:07,720 --> 00:05:12,280
 And today, we're going to look at, "I am the good shepherd."

102
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:14,920
 There's actually seven of those statements throughout the season.

103
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:16,720
 We're going to look at five.

104
00:05:16,720 --> 00:05:20,320
 And each of them point to the purpose of Jesus coming,

105
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:25,240
 and they just shed light on why we actually celebrate Christmas.

106
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:28,920
 So I hope that excites you, it excites me.

107
00:05:28,920 --> 00:05:33,320
 And so I want to go with you to our passage today.

108
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:35,360
 Before I do that, I just want to set a little context.

109
00:05:35,360 --> 00:05:39,520
 We're in the Gospel of John, we're in chapter 10.

110
00:05:39,520 --> 00:05:45,640
 And Jesus has been criticizing the religious leaders

111
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:50,920
 because the leaders have not cared for their people.

112
00:05:50,920 --> 00:05:56,000
 They have not done the job that God hasn't trusted them with.

113
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,640
 And because He hasn't done that job,

114
00:05:58,640 --> 00:06:03,400
 Jesus actually calls them thieves and robbers.

115
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:06,400
 I mean, if somebody calls you a thief and robber,

116
00:06:06,400 --> 00:06:08,760
 that's quite a strong language, right?

117
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:10,040
 Yikes.

118
00:06:10,040 --> 00:06:14,400
 But that's what He has said, they're thieves and robbers.

119
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:18,520
 And that's in this context of bad leadership, bad shepherding,

120
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:22,120
 that Jesus declares that He is the good shepherd.

121
00:06:22,120 --> 00:06:25,200
 So I want us to know that there's this contrast.

122
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:28,800
 He's just been criticizing bad leadership.

123
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:30,480
 So that's where I want to pick up.

124
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:35,120
 John chapter 10, verse 11, and it says this.

125
00:06:35,120 --> 00:06:37,760
 "I am the good shepherd.

126
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:42,600
 The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep.

127
00:06:42,600 --> 00:06:46,480
 The hired hand is not the shepherd and does not own the sheep.

128
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:52,680
 So when he sees the wolf coming, he abandons the sheep and runs away.

129
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:55,720
 Then the wolf attacks the flock and scatters it.

130
00:06:55,720 --> 00:06:58,800
 The man runs away because he's a hired hand

131
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:01,720
 and cares nothing for the sheep.

132
00:07:01,720 --> 00:07:03,360
 I am the good shepherd.

133
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:06,960
 I know my sheep and my sheep know me.

134
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:10,480
 Just as the Father knows me and I know the Father

135
00:07:10,480 --> 00:07:13,440
 and I lay down my life for the sheep,

136
00:07:13,440 --> 00:07:17,120
 I have other sheep that are not of this sheepfold.

137
00:07:17,120 --> 00:07:19,200
 I must bring them also.

138
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:21,840
 They too will listen to my voice

139
00:07:21,840 --> 00:07:26,160
 and there shall be one flock and one shepherd.

140
00:07:26,160 --> 00:07:30,440
 The reason my Father loves me is that I lay down my life

141
00:07:30,440 --> 00:07:32,360
 only to take it up again.

142
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:38,720
 No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord.

143
00:07:38,720 --> 00:07:43,720
 I have authority to lay it down and authority to take it up again.

144
00:07:43,720 --> 00:07:47,600
 This command I received from my Father."

145
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:53,000
 Now, I want to unpack this passage with you through two questions.

146
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:59,040
 So the first one is, what kind of shepherd is Jesus?

147
00:07:59,040 --> 00:08:03,160
 Like, he says he's good, but what does it mean that he's good?

148
00:08:03,160 --> 00:08:05,000
 So that's the first thing.

149
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,400
 And then the second thing that I want to look at with you is,

150
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:11,080
 how can we respond to this good shepherd?

151
00:08:11,080 --> 00:08:13,240
 Like, is there something we're supposed to do?

152
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:16,040
 And then of course, ultimately, is there something that we want to do

153
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:19,280
 in light of who this good shepherd is?

154
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:22,120
 So let's start with what kind of shepherd is Jesus?

155
00:08:22,120 --> 00:08:25,480
 He says in verse 11, "I am the good shepherd."

156
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:28,640
 And to truly grasp his goodness,

157
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:32,360
 we actually have to understand the bad shepherds,

158
00:08:32,360 --> 00:08:34,720
 the false shepherds, the thieves, the robbers,

159
00:08:34,720 --> 00:08:36,640
 and what's been happening there.

160
00:08:36,640 --> 00:08:41,880
 Now, in the ancient Near East, leaders were called shepherds.

161
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:44,800
 So not just in Israel, all over the place.

162
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:51,360
 And so civil leaders, kings, religious authorities,

163
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:53,960
 and God in the Old Testament,

164
00:08:53,960 --> 00:08:59,760
 he actually criticizes whenever his leaders fail to do the job

165
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:02,400
 that he has entrusted to them.

166
00:09:02,400 --> 00:09:06,000
 When they fail to reflect his heart,

167
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:07,600
 he calls them out through the prophets.

168
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:10,320
 For example, the prophet Ezekiel.

169
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:13,040
 Because they're supposed to care for the sheep,

170
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:17,040
 but he's confronting them because they're just caring about their own interest.

171
00:09:17,040 --> 00:09:19,880
 So you can read it in Ezekiel 34, the whole chapter.

172
00:09:19,880 --> 00:09:24,680
 It's incredible, and it's a background to our passage that we're looking at.

173
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:28,160
 But then Jesus, with his contemporaries,

174
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:32,080
 he's also called them out for being bad and false shepherds,

175
00:09:32,080 --> 00:09:33,880
 the religious leaders.

176
00:09:33,880 --> 00:09:38,640
 And they have just, before our past is shown their true colors,

177
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:42,600
 they have shown who they truly are.

178
00:09:42,600 --> 00:09:45,480
 In John 9, on the Sabbath,

179
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:50,080
 Jesus heals a blind man that was born blind.

180
00:09:50,080 --> 00:09:53,200
 Incredible, a miracle.

181
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:57,040
 But it's on the Sabbath where you're not supposed to work.

182
00:09:57,040 --> 00:10:00,680
 The religious leaders are like asking this guy to give a testimony.

183
00:10:00,680 --> 00:10:02,880
 What happened? He tells them, but they don't believe him.

184
00:10:02,880 --> 00:10:05,800
 So they ask his parents,

185
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:08,360
 you know, if their son was really blind, yes.

186
00:10:08,360 --> 00:10:10,400
 And then, again, they want more information,

187
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:13,360
 but the parents are already wisely wiggling their way through the answers

188
00:10:13,360 --> 00:10:16,600
 because they're fishing for something.

189
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:18,800
 And then they ask the blind man again what happened,

190
00:10:18,800 --> 00:10:21,800
 and they basically want the blind man to say that Jesus is a sinner

191
00:10:21,800 --> 00:10:24,720
 because he healed him on the Sabbath.

192
00:10:24,720 --> 00:10:26,080
 The blind man doesn't do that.

193
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:31,200
 He says, "All I know is I was blind, but now I see."

194
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:36,640
 And because of that, they kick him out of their community.

195
00:10:36,640 --> 00:10:41,120
 But just pause and think about what kind of leaders those are.

196
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:43,480
 They could care less about this person.

197
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:46,600
 They could care less about somebody who was suffering,

198
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:48,840
 who was not able to see.

199
00:10:48,840 --> 00:10:50,400
 They didn't care.

200
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:56,320
 They cared just about their own power and their own interest.

201
00:10:56,320 --> 00:11:00,360
 And Jesus was challenging that through his ministry, through his work,

202
00:11:00,360 --> 00:11:03,080
 because he was doing what shepherds were meant to do,

203
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:04,080
 what they were not doing.

204
00:11:04,080 --> 00:11:06,720
 It was exposing them.

205
00:11:06,720 --> 00:11:16,840
 And so it's this context where Jesus says, "I am the good shepherd."

206
00:11:16,840 --> 00:11:24,720
 Now, sadly, many of us, we, ourselves, have experienced bad shepherding,

207
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:27,240
 and to different degrees.

208
00:11:27,240 --> 00:11:33,760
 Maybe it's been a pastor in a church that turned out to be a crook.

209
00:11:33,760 --> 00:11:38,320
 Maybe it's been at a religious institution, a school, or a hospital,

210
00:11:38,320 --> 00:11:39,920
 or whatever else.

211
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:41,480
 I don't know.

212
00:11:41,480 --> 00:11:45,680
 I know when I was young, for a while, I went to a Christian school,

213
00:11:45,680 --> 00:11:47,360
 and I had a teacher who bullied me.

214
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:52,800
 I'm a kid, and a teacher bullies me.

215
00:11:52,800 --> 00:11:55,040
 And I wasn't sure, is it my fault?

216
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:58,240
 Is there something wrong with me?

217
00:11:58,240 --> 00:12:01,160
 So there are bad shepherds.

218
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:03,360
 They don't do what they're supposed to do.

219
00:12:03,360 --> 00:12:05,920
 And if that's been your experience, I just want to say,

220
00:12:05,920 --> 00:12:09,160
 I'm so thankful that you're here.

221
00:12:09,160 --> 00:12:15,520
 I hope that we can be a safe place for you to encounter Jesus,

222
00:12:15,520 --> 00:12:20,080
 to pursue Jesus, to heal.

223
00:12:20,080 --> 00:12:21,160
 That's my heart for us.

224
00:12:21,160 --> 00:12:29,760
 But when Jesus says, "I'm the good shepherd," it's not just about,

225
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:33,480
 "I'm not a bad shepherd," but he's also making a declaration

226
00:12:33,480 --> 00:12:38,040
 about his identity, about who he is.

227
00:12:38,040 --> 00:12:42,720
 And there's an Old Testament context to this, because there's expectations.

228
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:48,000
 Israel was longing, waiting, yearning for the shepherd to come,

229
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:51,240
 the finally truly shepherded people.

230
00:12:51,240 --> 00:12:57,680
 I want to take you to Ezekiel 34, where in verse 15, it talks about this,

231
00:12:57,680 --> 00:13:00,160
 or where actually God talks about what he's going to do

232
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:01,400
 in response to bad shepherds.

233
00:13:01,400 --> 00:13:07,760
 He says this, "I myself would tend my sheep and make them lie down,"

234
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:09,960
 declares the sovereign Lord.

235
00:13:09,960 --> 00:13:13,840
 "I would search for the lost, bring back the strays.

236
00:13:13,840 --> 00:13:18,120
 I will bind up the injured and strengthen the weak.

237
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:20,920
 But the sleek and the strong I will destroy.

238
00:13:20,920 --> 00:13:23,320
 I will shepherd the flock with justice."

239
00:13:26,960 --> 00:13:31,880
 So when Jesus calls himself the good shepherd, he's saying,

240
00:13:31,880 --> 00:13:36,560
 "I am the long-awaited Messiah.

241
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:42,280
 I am the good shepherd who will finally bring back the lost sheep,

242
00:13:42,280 --> 00:13:46,480
 the harassed sheep, the herding sheep, and I will restore them back

243
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:51,080
 to the flock, and I will bring wholeness where there is brokenness.

244
00:13:55,080 --> 00:13:59,360
 And there is no circumstance for this shepherd that he does not know

245
00:13:59,360 --> 00:14:03,880
 how to lead through, how to guide, or how to provide.

246
00:14:03,880 --> 00:14:06,080
 He is the good shepherd."

247
00:14:06,080 --> 00:14:17,880
 But how can we truly be confident that he's the good shepherd?

248
00:14:17,880 --> 00:14:20,040
 Now, somebody can say they're the good shepherd.

249
00:14:20,040 --> 00:14:22,760
 How do you know that?

250
00:14:22,760 --> 00:14:26,080
 Well, that's what we find out in verse 11 with the second part.

251
00:14:26,080 --> 00:14:28,360
 He says, "I am the good shepherd.

252
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:31,800
 The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep."

253
00:14:31,800 --> 00:14:42,000
 So he's talking about, "I laid down my life on a cross for you,

254
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,360
 on behalf of you, instead of you."

255
00:14:47,280 --> 00:14:54,440
 He took the penalty that we deserve for our sin upon himself so that we can

256
00:14:54,440 --> 00:14:58,600
 be forgiven, that we can be made whole, that we can be restored

257
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:04,480
 into this shepherding relationship with the heavenly Father.

258
00:15:04,480 --> 00:15:12,800
 He laid down his life for you and me.

259
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:16,480
 Now, that's putting your money where your mouth is at,

260
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:19,240
 to use an American expression.

261
00:15:19,240 --> 00:15:21,440
 It means you put something into action.

262
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:24,720
 You don't just talk, you actually do something.

263
00:15:24,720 --> 00:15:25,720
 Excuse me.

264
00:15:25,720 --> 00:15:43,480
 You know, when somebody doesn't withhold any love and care from you and gives

265
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:50,680
 everything they have, laying down his life, dying for you,

266
00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:54,840
 you know, the good shepherd is for you.

267
00:15:54,840 --> 00:15:55,720
 He loves you.

268
00:15:55,720 --> 00:15:58,440
 He's not against you.

269
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:00,080
 He doesn't withhold anything.

270
00:16:00,080 --> 00:16:02,080
 He gives everything.

271
00:16:02,080 --> 00:16:07,680
 He loves you perfectly.

272
00:16:07,680 --> 00:16:11,880
 Now, no human leader can love everyone perfectly.

273
00:16:11,880 --> 00:16:14,520
 Only Jesus can.

274
00:16:14,520 --> 00:16:15,880
 Only the good shepherd can.

275
00:16:15,880 --> 00:16:21,000
 Human leaders, you know, ate us horrible once, and then we're all still broken

276
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,360
 people to one degree or another.

277
00:16:23,360 --> 00:16:27,120
 But Jesus is the perfect good shepherd.

278
00:16:27,120 --> 00:16:29,720
 He loves you.

279
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:34,520
 Jesus proves he's the good shepherd by putting us first.

280
00:16:34,520 --> 00:16:40,120
 He laid down his life on the cross without hesitation for our benefit.

281
00:16:41,120 --> 00:16:46,280
 Now, we often struggle to believe that.

282
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:48,000
 Actually, that's a lot of the Christian journey.

283
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:51,400
 We struggle to believe that God is really good, that he really loves us,

284
00:16:51,400 --> 00:16:53,360
 that he really cares about us.

285
00:16:53,360 --> 00:16:57,480
 And maybe some of us are struggling with that right now.

286
00:16:57,480 --> 00:17:04,960
 And I just want to share a story from an author that I'm going to retell that kind

287
00:17:04,960 --> 00:17:05,840
 of speaks to that.

288
00:17:05,840 --> 00:17:11,520
 So, Philip Yancey, he, I should say now, he probably was a well-known author.

289
00:17:11,520 --> 00:17:13,240
 And he wrote a book quite a while ago.

290
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:17,280
 It's called "The Jesus I Never Knew."

291
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:20,960
 And so, in this book, he tells a story from a Harvard professor or actually the

292
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:23,120
 Harvard chaplain.

293
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:28,360
 And a student came into this chaplain's office, sits down, she sits down,

294
00:17:28,360 --> 00:17:30,760
 she's like, "I don't believe in God."

295
00:17:30,760 --> 00:17:33,440
 He's like, "Welcome."

296
00:17:33,440 --> 00:17:39,040
 And in his wise way as a chaplain, he asked, "Well, tell me about the God that

297
00:17:39,040 --> 00:17:40,360
 you don't believe in.

298
00:17:40,360 --> 00:17:41,840
 Just tell me about him."

299
00:17:41,840 --> 00:17:45,120
 And so, she tells him why she doesn't believe in God and what upsets her and

300
00:17:45,120 --> 00:17:47,160
 what angers her about God.

301
00:17:47,160 --> 00:17:50,320
 And she just pours all that out and he listens.

302
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:56,880
 And then he says, "You know, I don't believe in that God either.

303
00:17:56,880 --> 00:18:01,400
 But let me show you the God that I believe in."

304
00:18:01,400 --> 00:18:06,360
 So he pulls out the Bible and he opens up to the Gospels and he start looking

305
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:11,680
 at Jesus because Jesus is God with us.

306
00:18:11,680 --> 00:18:15,880
 You know, our understandings of God, they're often off.

307
00:18:15,880 --> 00:18:21,520
 You know, whether we pick them up from our parents or from random stuff,

308
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:23,240
 life experiences.

309
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:26,200
 But when we look at Jesus, we see God in flesh.

310
00:18:26,200 --> 00:18:28,800
 We see who Jesus truly is.

311
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:37,120
 We see how Jesus relates to us, how he feels about us, how he thinks about us,

312
00:18:37,120 --> 00:18:41,680
 how we can stand in relationship with him.

313
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:50,280
 And the most clearly where we see how Jesus feels about us is on the cross.

314
00:18:50,280 --> 00:18:59,880
 The most powerful revelation of his love for you, for me, for all of humanity.

315
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:02,880
 Jesus loves us so much.

316
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:04,320
 He loves you so much.

317
00:19:04,320 --> 00:19:08,920
 He loves the people around you so much that he laid down his life on the cross.

318
00:19:08,920 --> 00:19:13,520
 So if you ever wonder about how God feels about you, you look at the cross,

319
00:19:13,520 --> 00:19:17,720
 that's how he feels about you.

320
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:23,680
 And so when we struggle with God's goodness, you know, one thing we can do is

321
00:19:23,680 --> 00:19:25,800
 we can look at Jesus.

322
00:19:25,800 --> 00:19:28,800
 So maybe if you're struggling, maybe that's something for you to do.

323
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:32,240
 Just open, you know, we have our own thoughts, but maybe we need to hold them

324
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:38,520
 up against God's word, against how Jesus has revealed himself, who he is.

325
00:19:38,520 --> 00:19:42,560
 Not who we say he is, but who he truly is.

326
00:19:42,560 --> 00:19:50,560
 So maybe that's what you need to do and spend some time with.

327
00:19:50,560 --> 00:19:56,440
 But Jesus not only is he the good shepherd who lays down his life for us,

328
00:19:56,440 --> 00:20:00,640
 but he's also the shepherd who knows his sheep.

329
00:20:00,640 --> 00:20:08,240
 And in John 14, it says this, "I know my sheep and my sheep know me."

330
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:14,480
 Now the verb ginosko in Greek, not Greece, it's also in Greece, but ginosko,

331
00:20:14,480 --> 00:20:18,360
 it's an experiential knowledge.

332
00:20:18,360 --> 00:20:22,160
 It's not just a, "I know your name, I know facts about you."

333
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:23,800
 It's like, "I know you through relation."

334
00:20:23,800 --> 00:20:25,480
 It's a relational knowledge.

335
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:30,080
 "I know you relationally.

336
00:20:30,080 --> 00:20:34,120
 I know my sheep and my sheep know me."

337
00:20:34,120 --> 00:20:40,440
 So Jesus is a good shepherd whom you can truly know relationally.

338
00:20:40,440 --> 00:20:48,800
 And what's incredible is that Jesus, he knows everything about you and me.

339
00:20:48,800 --> 00:20:54,480
 He knows our past histories, the good stuff, the bad stuff.

340
00:20:54,480 --> 00:20:56,640
 He knows last week.

341
00:20:56,640 --> 00:20:58,760
 He knows our thoughts.

342
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:01,160
 He knows everything.

343
00:21:01,160 --> 00:21:03,360
 But he loves you.

344
00:21:03,360 --> 00:21:07,760
 He loves you.

345
00:21:07,760 --> 00:21:14,200
 In Romans 5, 8, the Apostle Paul, he says this, "But God demonstrated his own love for

346
00:21:14,200 --> 00:21:15,440
 us in this.

347
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:20,360
 While we were sinners, Christ died for us."

348
00:21:20,360 --> 00:21:25,800
 So it doesn't say that he died for us only once we had our act together, only once we

349
00:21:25,800 --> 00:21:27,720
 lived perfect lives.

350
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:31,840
 It says that he died for you and me when we were sinners.

351
00:21:31,840 --> 00:21:38,040
 That means he loved us when we were broken, messed up people, doing messed up things.

352
00:21:38,040 --> 00:21:40,400
 He loves you.

353
00:21:40,400 --> 00:21:43,360
 His love doesn't fluctuate based on how you behave.

354
00:21:43,360 --> 00:21:45,160
 He loves you.

355
00:21:45,160 --> 00:21:48,040
 It's hard, right?

356
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:54,160
 It's hard for us to comprehend that type of love.

357
00:21:54,160 --> 00:22:01,040
 Jesus looks at you with delight and not disgust.

358
00:22:01,040 --> 00:22:05,680
 You are his absolute treasure.

359
00:22:05,680 --> 00:22:07,600
 You are his absolute treasure.

360
00:22:07,600 --> 00:22:14,760
 Now a lot of times we feel like that somehow we're disgusting to God.

361
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:18,400
 But again, if we look at Jesus, we see that's not true.

362
00:22:18,400 --> 00:22:20,920
 You're not disgusting to God.

363
00:22:20,920 --> 00:22:22,640
 He loves you.

364
00:22:22,640 --> 00:22:25,300
 He delights in you.

365
00:22:25,300 --> 00:22:26,920
 You are his treasure.

366
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:30,080
 You are the reason why he came for Christmas.

367
00:22:30,080 --> 00:22:31,080
 Why we celebrate Christmas.

368
00:22:31,080 --> 00:22:36,240
 You're the reason why he was incarnated, why he was born, why he humbled himself, even

369
00:22:36,240 --> 00:22:42,680
 though he's God, to come to us, to show us his love.

370
00:22:42,680 --> 00:22:44,360
 He loves you.

371
00:22:44,360 --> 00:22:47,040
 You are worth it.

372
00:22:47,040 --> 00:22:54,800
 You are so worth it.

373
00:22:54,800 --> 00:23:01,200
 You know, for me, I was thinking of when Chris and I, my wife, when we started first dating,

374
00:23:01,200 --> 00:23:05,680
 I was like, "I have baggage.

375
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:07,600
 I have issues.

376
00:23:07,600 --> 00:23:10,280
 I just want her to know."

377
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:12,160
 You know, because I don't want stuff to come up later.

378
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:15,040
 And she's like, "Oh, no, thanks."

379
00:23:15,040 --> 00:23:17,680
 It's like, "This is who I am.

380
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:21,480
 Here's all my stuff, my anxieties, my issues."

381
00:23:21,480 --> 00:23:26,800
 And you know, it's incredible when somebody loves you.

382
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:29,640
 They just love you.

383
00:23:29,640 --> 00:23:35,440
 And in a similar way, and how much more, you know, God loves us.

384
00:23:35,440 --> 00:23:36,440
 He knows all your baggage.

385
00:23:36,440 --> 00:23:37,440
 He knows all your junk.

386
00:23:37,440 --> 00:23:39,960
 He knows all your past histories.

387
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:43,440
 But he loves you.

388
00:23:43,440 --> 00:23:53,380
 He deeply loves you.

389
00:23:53,380 --> 00:23:55,400
 And we can know his love.

390
00:23:55,400 --> 00:24:04,040
 You know, there's peace, there's security when you're loved.

391
00:24:04,040 --> 00:24:07,520
 There's healing when you're loved.

392
00:24:07,520 --> 00:24:13,280
 You know how loving it is to be just—how healing it is to just be loved.

393
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:20,640
 So powerful.

394
00:24:20,640 --> 00:24:23,280
 Let me give you a last one for why Jesus is a good shepherd, even though I think we already

395
00:24:23,280 --> 00:24:26,000
 covered some good ground here, right?

396
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:34,200
 Jesus is a good shepherd because he has authority and power that is unmatched.

397
00:24:34,200 --> 00:24:40,240
 Verse 17 and 18 says this, "I lay down my life only to take it up again.

398
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:44,560
 No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord.

399
00:24:44,560 --> 00:24:50,440
 I have authority to lay it down and authority to take it up again."

400
00:24:50,440 --> 00:24:53,240
 So it's important to see here, Jesus wasn't an accident.

401
00:24:53,240 --> 00:24:56,440
 He died and it was just bad circumstances.

402
00:24:56,440 --> 00:25:01,080
 No, he was in control.

403
00:25:01,080 --> 00:25:05,040
 He died because he wanted to die for us.

404
00:25:05,040 --> 00:25:07,960
 This was not some historical accident.

405
00:25:07,960 --> 00:25:10,840
 You know, he did it out of an act of free will.

406
00:25:10,840 --> 00:25:15,800
 We earlier, Pastor Chapman, talked about self-giving love because he just, again, he just loves

407
00:25:15,800 --> 00:25:17,240
 you.

408
00:25:17,240 --> 00:25:20,360
 But then the amazing thing is he has authority to also take back up his life.

409
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:26,040
 So we not only celebrate Jesus' death, we also celebrate that Jesus rose, that he overcame

410
00:25:26,040 --> 00:25:32,440
 death, that he is mightier, that he's stronger, that he's more powerful than even death because

411
00:25:32,440 --> 00:25:36,480
 his authority is unmatched.

412
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:41,440
 He is all powerful.

413
00:25:41,440 --> 00:25:46,920
 You know, that's also amazing when you're looking for a good shepherd, when somebody

414
00:25:46,920 --> 00:25:56,100
 has unmatched authority and power who is leading and guiding you, but who is truly good and

415
00:25:56,100 --> 00:25:58,600
 only has good purposes for you.

416
00:25:58,600 --> 00:26:03,240
 So somebody who actually uses the power in the right way.

417
00:26:03,240 --> 00:26:06,320
 That's amazing.

418
00:26:06,320 --> 00:26:12,960
 He has the power to care for us, the power to forgive sins, the power to give abundant

419
00:26:12,960 --> 00:26:20,880
 life, the power to feed enemies, the power to overcome death, and the power to provide

420
00:26:20,880 --> 00:26:25,720
 for every need that we may face in our life.

421
00:26:25,720 --> 00:26:28,280
 Every season.

422
00:26:28,280 --> 00:26:33,040
 Jesus' authority and power is unmatched.

423
00:26:33,040 --> 00:26:37,520
 He is truly the good shepherd.

424
00:26:37,520 --> 00:26:44,240
 But now, how can we respond to this?

425
00:26:44,240 --> 00:26:49,640
 How are we being invited by the Holy Spirit to respond as we just slowed down and looked

426
00:26:49,640 --> 00:26:54,920
 at the good shepherd?

427
00:26:54,920 --> 00:26:57,600
 Our passage shows us two ways that we can respond.

428
00:26:57,600 --> 00:27:00,760
 And actually what's interesting, it's really about the faithfulness of the shepherd in

429
00:27:00,760 --> 00:27:01,880
 this passage.

430
00:27:01,880 --> 00:27:03,320
 That's really the focus.

431
00:27:03,320 --> 00:27:07,680
 But there's two ways of responding that are implied in that.

432
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:13,200
 The first one is it invites us to surrender to his leadership.

433
00:27:13,200 --> 00:27:18,360
 Because being a sheep means that Jesus is the leader of your life.

434
00:27:18,360 --> 00:27:24,320
 It means that we don't sit in the driver's seat, so instead of us saying, "I am the maker

435
00:27:24,320 --> 00:27:25,800
 of my own fate.

436
00:27:25,800 --> 00:27:27,400
 I know what's best for me.

437
00:27:27,400 --> 00:27:31,960
 I'm going to do whatever I feel like and want to do."

438
00:27:31,960 --> 00:27:34,760
 It means we surrender to the leadership of Jesus.

439
00:27:34,760 --> 00:27:36,600
 That we say, "I trust you.

440
00:27:36,600 --> 00:27:38,240
 I trust your leadership.

441
00:27:38,240 --> 00:27:43,880
 I trust that what you ask me to do is better than what I know.

442
00:27:43,880 --> 00:27:45,800
 And I'm going to do it."

443
00:27:45,800 --> 00:27:53,740
 So being surrendered to the leadership of Jesus means that we do what Jesus asks us

444
00:27:53,740 --> 00:27:56,960
 to do.

445
00:27:56,960 --> 00:28:01,640
 But it all starts ultimately, it begins with becoming a Christian.

446
00:28:01,640 --> 00:28:06,120
 That we say, "Jesus, I need you in my life.

447
00:28:06,120 --> 00:28:09,160
 I've been doing things my own way.

448
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:11,600
 It's not working or it's not working well.

449
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:13,680
 And I just know I need you.

450
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:18,360
 So I want to ask you that you come into my life, that you become the leader of my life."

451
00:28:18,360 --> 00:28:22,840
 Then when we do that, God's word says that we are filled with the Holy Spirit.

452
00:28:22,840 --> 00:28:25,800
 We are born again.

453
00:28:25,800 --> 00:28:33,040
 We receive a new life, abundant life, the life of God's goodness.

454
00:28:33,040 --> 00:28:37,700
 But then even as a sheep, even as Christians, we still are wayward.

455
00:28:37,700 --> 00:28:43,840
 We still go off and do our own things and go back into, "I know better."

456
00:28:43,840 --> 00:28:49,560
 And so there's this call to surrender to his leadership.

457
00:28:49,560 --> 00:28:54,920
 Psalm 38 says, "Taste and see that the Lord is good."

458
00:28:54,920 --> 00:29:01,560
 When we surrender to his leadership, we get to taste and see that his leadership is good.

459
00:29:01,560 --> 00:29:05,840
 Because when we do that, when we do what he says, we actually give God space to work in

460
00:29:05,840 --> 00:29:11,400
 our lives and pour out his goodness over our lives.

461
00:29:11,400 --> 00:29:15,400
 I preached a couple of weeks ago where I said when we step out in faith, when we do what

462
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:17,400
 he says, God shows up.

463
00:29:17,400 --> 00:29:22,500
 But the only way you're going to figure out that God shows up is when we actually listen

464
00:29:22,500 --> 00:29:24,280
 to him.

465
00:29:24,280 --> 00:29:28,920
 When we live surrendered lives to him.

466
00:29:28,920 --> 00:29:33,520
 And it's amazing how he shows up, even when we struggle to picture that he can.

467
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:35,960
 But he does time and time again.

468
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:38,680
 That's a testimony of people here in the church.

469
00:29:38,680 --> 00:29:44,360
 That's my testimony.

470
00:29:44,360 --> 00:29:55,880
 The second way that we're invited to respond is to enjoy the care of the Good Shepherd.

471
00:29:55,880 --> 00:29:58,880
 To be a sheep.

472
00:29:58,880 --> 00:30:04,480
 Now a lot of times we talk about all these things we're supposed to do, but I think the

473
00:30:04,480 --> 00:30:14,520
 Good Shepherd is inviting us just to enjoy his care, just to dwell in his goodness, to

474
00:30:14,520 --> 00:30:26,760
 be under his leadership and care, to enjoy his love, to be blessed by his guidance.

475
00:30:26,760 --> 00:30:30,840
 So we get to just be.

476
00:30:30,840 --> 00:30:34,720
 When we're constantly running around somewhere needing to perform and create something, make

477
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:39,520
 something happen, well when you are under the care of the Good Shepherd you just get

478
00:30:39,520 --> 00:30:40,520
 to be.

479
00:30:40,520 --> 00:30:43,840
 You just get to rest.

480
00:30:43,840 --> 00:30:46,080
 You don't have to know everything.

481
00:30:46,080 --> 00:30:51,200
 You don't have to have the 20 year plan for your life.

482
00:30:51,200 --> 00:30:56,360
 You just entrust yourself to the Shepherd and he will accomplish his purposes that he

483
00:30:56,360 --> 00:30:59,760
 has for you in your life.

484
00:30:59,760 --> 00:31:07,200
 His goodness and mercy will follow you all the days of your life.

485
00:31:07,200 --> 00:31:20,680
 So I want to invite the worship team to come up.

486
00:31:20,680 --> 00:31:26,520
 Don't just celebrate Christmas this year and let it just rush towards you and you just

487
00:31:26,520 --> 00:31:31,440
 do your thing, you just go through the motions.

488
00:31:31,440 --> 00:31:38,480
 Actually respond to the Good Shepherd.

489
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:42,640
 Put yourself under his love and his care.

490
00:31:42,640 --> 00:31:45,680
 Surrender to his leadership.

491
00:31:45,680 --> 00:31:58,240
 Release the security and the peace that is only found under the care of the Good Shepherd.

492
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:03,160
 You know scripture talks about there is peace with God, that's when we're restored in our

493
00:32:03,160 --> 00:32:07,920
 relationship with the Good Shepherd because our relationship with God is broken when we

